description.text: My thing http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1563812 was a really quick and easy 3D-printable screw-in front lenscap design, set-up as a customizer application. This enhanced version not only supports everything that did, but also allows creating custom screw-in filter holders. Basically, this can now make screw-in versions of the solar filters my thing https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2475342 made as bayonet-mount for the Canon SX530 HS. The two-piece design sandwiches AstroSolar film to make filter -- just as was described in my instructable about the SX530 HS filter: https://www.instructables.com/id/Safely-Shooting-the-Sun-With-the-Canon-PowerShot-S/

Notes:

The solar filter material we recommend is AstroSolar Safety film, http://astrosolar.com/en/ , which is a 0.01mm thick material. It doesn't matter if it has little waves in it as mounted, but you don't want to stretch it. Thus, print the two pieces, make sure they fit reasonably (remove any print defects such as stray hairs), and then spray contact cement on the side of the threaded half that was printed facing down. Once that has partially dried, simply press that onto the film. The film can then be trimmed to the edge of the part. Finally, the second part is fitted over the film and a soldering iron is used to permanently weld the two pieces together. This is essentially the same process described in https://www.instructables.com/id/Safely-Shooting-the-Sun-With-the-Canon-PowerShot-S/

Note that the 20170816 version is now replaced with a 20170820 version that has thicker sidewalls on the grip for larger-diameter filter holders. The earlier version is still perfectly usable, but the extra rigidity helps.

title: 2020 Cable Zip Tie Mount for M5x10 screws (optional fins)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
What is this?

A mount that attaches to 2020 extrusion profiles through which you can run your cables and secure them with a ziptie.

Why did I create this?

I initially intended to use the 2020 Cable Zip Tie Mount by joochung for my Anet A8 AM8 conversion, but the original design required M5x8 screws which I didn't have (the AM8 uses M5x10 button head screws). The M5x10 proved to long to properly secure the mount, so I redid the original but raised its height by 2mm (5 instead of 7), which gave me the neccessary clearance.

I left the other specifications as they were, so the mount still uses an M5 screw and the hole for the ziptie measures 5x2mm.

I also created to additional version with some fins both vertically and horizontally to slot into the extrusion profile and assure proper alignment. The versions with the fins are harder to print and will require support. I know, it's a bit ugly, but I saw no other way.

Misc

This file was initially published in my 3D-Printing Github repository.

Version History

  • 1.0 - initial release
  • 1.0.1 - fins were not truly centered, changed offset to make them centered

description.text:
GitHub repo with latest Files --> https://github.com/splosch/tension_b

"Tension Bee"

Sketch of a super lightweight, easy assembly drone frame that is made sturdy by tension.

Files

The Project was created with 123D Design from autodesk
STLs of the Parts & 123D Files are attached
The STLs of the Connectors can be 3D Printed right away without support

Idea

Some flat & flexible bars e.g. Carbon Fiber or Glass Fiber flatbars are connected with simple / angled connectors in to a ring-shape. At least 2 but more edges can be used - in this demo 4 connectors form a ring-shape structure.

This structure can easily be assembled but will fall apart easily as well :)

But if now tension is applied towards the center of the contraption e.g. with fishing-line or carbon rods.
The ring stabilizes and gets quite sturdy to bending from and towards the center.

Still flexing of corners is possible. By using an angled tensioning approach to each corner the contraption gets stury in all directions.

One of the weak-points here is the flexed flat-bar, which if made out of Carbon-Fiber is actually pushing against the connectors - which could make them splinter if force is applied.

The Example uses standard Brushed Motors available for Drones (e.g. JJRC H29, H29C, H29W, H29G Quadcopter)
and is made for 5mm x 1mm (CF / GF)Flatbars of any length, "Spring-Metall" or wood might also work

This project allows you to make your own electric screwdriver like Xiaomi Wowstick.

Print both parts with flat side down. The Tsang model should be printed vertically.

The screwdriver body guts consist of four main blocks.

First: The charger board
The CB I used is a LiIon charger from China with indicator LEDs and undercharge protection. In the right side of the body there is a well for charge state indicators (red/blue). It can be filled with some transparent hot glue or plugged with a piece of acrylic window. I left it as is.
Example: http://www.ebay.com/itm/1A-Micro-USB-18650-Lithium-Battery-Charging-Module-LED-Charger-Board-Protection-/112520617292

Second: LiIon 18650 cell
Here you can use almost any 18650 cell, for example from old laptop battery. The capacity of cell will effect the working time of screwdriver. In my case the consumption was around 30-100 mA, so it will work very long.

Third: The Switch
You will need a DPDT ON-OFF-ON switch with 6 pins to make the screwdriver work both directions and wil be possible to turn it off.
Example: http://www.ebay.com/itm/20Pcs-AC-125V-6A-ON-OFF-ON-DPDT-Locking-Mini-Toggle-Switch-Blue-6mm-K4G4-/262846034205

Fourth: The motor
In my project a micro DC motor with metal gearbox and speed reduction is used.
You will need a motor for 3v or 6v with 160-300 RPM. The lower RPM is the higher is the torque, but you can fall asleep while the screw will come out. I used 160 rpm 6v motor, but is is neither powerful enough to loosen a screw nor fast enough to make it good. I upgraded the model with a brake button so it is now possible to put a 300 RPM motor for fast working and use brakes to tighten or loosen nuts and screws.

title: L-Boxx bit/hex-shaft holder

description.text:
A basic bit holder for the lid of a L-Boxx. Didn't like the fact that the crappy box of Bosch's own Multi Construction Bits doesn't fit in the Box. Even for the Impact bit set, I had to modify the box. So I designed a simple holder which can be screwed to the lid. Five clamps are two millimeters deeper so long bits don't wiggle as much.

UPDATE: There was a wrong measurement, so the clip snaps. I uploaded BitholderLboxxFixed.stl with 6.35 mm and also increased the thickness of the clip. I haven't tested this version, but I'll try this weekend.
Thanks to philklaus for the correction!

Notes:

Printed with 0.4 nozzle.
Set extrusion width to 0.48, so there are no gaps in the clamps.
Print with ABS or PETG, PLA might snap more easily

Mounting

I used self-tapping screws for plastic. The length of the thread is 11.5 mm, the diameter is 3 mm. Using a shorter screw is possible, longer will make white marks on the top of the lid. Using standard M3 (M3x10 should work) screws could work, but I haven't tested it. Please comment if it works, thanks!

title: QuadFloat - Float Your Drone or Quad

description.text:
I wanted to fly over some pretty deep water in situations where a rope or large jets of water might take out my quad. The quad is largely made up of junk parts, so I don't care too much about losing it. That being said, the GoPro is not something I'm willing to part with that easily and littering a lithium battery and whatnot into the lake is something I'd like to avoid.

The formula I used was to weigh my quad with everything attached (including the float) in grams. Find a bottle with an equivalent number of of ml (which is equivalent to cc's or cm^3) + 15% or so. A displaced ml of water weighs ~1g and I believe you'll need to displace about as many grams of water as your quad weighs plus some. If you float only as many g as your quad weighs - the quad won't float as much as touch the surface ... so you'll want a little extra floatation to keep it on the surface. In my case the nearest bottle size that was close to my limit was 23.7oz or ~700cc.

I'm ignoring the water that the frame / battery / etc... displaces because I couldn't think of a reliable way to calculate that without dunking the quad. The quad is waterproofed with conformal coating, but I still don't want to put it in the water unless I need to.

TWO VERSIONS: Both attach with zip ties / cable ties (I also used a little VHB tape to keep things from sliding around). For both - I use two for each side of the bottle (front and back) to make a flat surface for both the base of your quad and the ground for takeoff. Depending on your level of risk tolerance there are two versions one with space for 4 cable ties and one with space for 2 cable ties. I used a combination ... plus a string attached to the bottle top as a last resort. Because I'm a wimp :)

ANYWAYS! Enjoy! Let me know if you use it, please!

Your design sorts out both those fails, thank you for your time and efforts :)

10/13/17 Update:
Added a 1mm radius fillet along the top and bottom edge of the spacer.

In the Audi/VW community, a common modification for 1.8T and 2.7T engines is to use coilpacks from a newer model 2.0T direct injection engine. The 2.0T has a higher output coil and is mostly a plug and play modification depending on the engine code, however the coil is longer and sticks out of the cylinder head about 10mm. This spacer is simply used to fill that gap and help prevent dirt and debris from falling into the plug hole.

The spacer uses two (2) M6 socket cap screws to fasten it to the valve cover.

Many aftermarket companies offer this spacer, but made of billet aluminum. Each one is slightly different in shape, but important dimensions such as bolt hole size and spacing, thickness of spacer and coil hole size are the same.

Due to the temperatures in the engine bay, ABS or Nylon would be a suitable material choice.

title: E3D v6 and Titan extruder Cyclone layer fan Makergear M2

description.text:
30mm extruder fan mount plus magnetic quick detach cyclonic layer fan.

Uses two 8x2mm neodynium magnets (one in each part), which then allows for quick removal of the layer fan shroud for easy maintenance/nozzle clearing. If you don't care about that, the two parts can simply be glued together.

Fan shroud is 270 degrees to allow extruder to move fully to the right for a pre-print purge. Works best with the heater block orientated "backwards", long part towards the back of the printer (see mounted photos).

Radial Fan simply slots on the top of the downtube.

Depending on your print calibration/settings, you may need to lightly massage the locating tabs with a needle file as they are designed to be a tight fit to avoid wobble. You may also like to pre-drill the fan mounting holes to make screwing the fan mount screws in easier depending on what mount screws you are using.

Been getting great results with it, very even and all round airflow distribution, 100% is very powerful and I find 40% works extremely well with formfutura TitanX which is what it is printed in.

I printed the radial fan shroud upright, and the 30mm fan mount with the fan face down. Your mileage may vary.

Edit - slightly tweaked the 30mm fan mount dimensions. If you were an early downloader then would recommend you re-download that part. Nothing major, just slightly shallower tab to sit more square against Titan extruder body and a smidge more clearance in the female tab alignment slots.

description.text:
This is my first attempt to make something serious.

I followed the recommendations for a ported design from here:
http://www.d-s-t.com.au/data/Peerless/Peerless_XLS_Subwoofer.pdf

The front and rear baffle are mounted on a ~10" (actually 250 mm) sonotube with a length of 450mm or 17.71"

Either print the front and rear baffles whole or use the chopped up sections. 6 sections per baffle.

Assemble the baffle sections and mount the peerless xls10.

Use six M8 or M10 threaded rods to put it all together. drill som pilot holes for the feet and screw them on place.

As a port pipe I used ~3" or 75mm outer diameter drainage pipe. depending how the pipe corner pieces are made calculate the total length for each section to get a ~930mm long pipe

I printed all parts with a 0.6mm nozzle and 50% infill.

remember that this will need several spools of filament. Rear baffle alone took 1.7kg for me to print.

Edit

I notice now that I named the parts mostly in Swedish... I designed it vertically in the CAD software so:
"Övre" means upper but is front
and
Nedre means lower but is back.

description.text:
I customized a few of the parts for my AM8 frame. Specifically...

  • Made modular mounts for the mosfets, Anet board and Raspberry Pi so you can print these separate and mix, match and arrange as you like. I added standoffs with 3.2mm holes which can accept either a 3mm bolt / nut or a #6 3/8" or less self tapping screw (SAE is easier to come by and cheaper in the U.S. for obvious reasons). These were made / remixed based on pheneey's original Anet board mount from the AM8 metal frame thing.
  • Remixed thaug29's z-rod holders with bearings back to the orginal design and included his bearing holders but with the bearings put in from the top rather than the bottom (too worried that over time the bearings would come lose and drop down the threaded z-rods).
  • Remixed Construtor's spool holder to have smaller mounts and require less bolts to hold on to the frame.
  • Remixed thaug29's bowden extruder mount for 2040 extruded aluminum.
  • Remixed gmars23's alignment tool to be used for aligning the y rod holders at 52mm from each end. Also note that the round side of the holder should face outward so that there is less chance of colliding with the bed leveling nuts (wing nuts are a bit of a problem since they are so big so use one of the many bed leveling nuts for the A8). If you face the wrong way, the alignment tool will not be the correct distance to center the bed y rods since the y rod holders are not symmetrical. Also cmccr88's remix of the y rod holder with the y stop switch mount. It will have the round side of the holder facing outward to avoid colliding with the bed leveling nuts. For completeness, his version is included here and has not been altered.
  • I remixed this y belt attachment (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1648888) to be 30mm long so it wouldn't bang into the y-axis motor mount.

Be warned, I haven't actually printed / used these yet as I am still in process of my build, so print at your own risk :). Not sure how well the bearing holder will print now that it isn't on the print bed so supports may be necessary. So I did a v5 with a 0.8mm ridge on the bottom that is enough to keep the bearing in place and print ok.

Additional note to these building the AM8 frame...order lots of extra button head M5x10 screws and M5 square nuts! You will want to bolt more things to your new frame.

title: Car w/ moving wheels (no assembly required)

description.text: I'm no car designer, so don't make fun of my design! :) However, this car should be fun to play with. Make sure it prints on its side. It rolls best on rough terrain but can roll on paper. If you want to scale it I recommend not going past 75% otherwise the detail will start disappearing. Windows are slightly slanted and may require supports for better detail but everything else does not need supports. Once it is printed turn the wheels to break any unwanted attachment and you may need to cut the axle holder a bit on the edges to make sure there is no friction. If the spoiler (wing) breaks I recommend soldering it back on or super gluing. This may seem crazy to solder but you take your solder pen and melt the wing back together and taking some of the filament you have and melting it on to the spoiler. This is quite dangerous but it works very well don't do this without supervision and stay away from the fumes that come off especially if you are using ABS because believe it or not they are sightly toxic (use a mask). I hope there is enjoyment and leave a comment if any questions arise.

description.text:
This is a sensor mount for the SN04-N sensor which replaces the stock sensor mount from Anet or third parties. I found the 3mm acrylic plate mount was quite bendy and couldn't be firmly fixed. This design adds ribs which are not only anti-bend, but butt against the linear bearings to give a solid fixing. I also added nut recesses so you can adjust the sensor height more easily (without having to hold the nuts in place).

I found that when placing the sensor in the same position as the stock mount, and with a firm fixing to the carriage, the autohome on X axis could jam as the sensor butts against the frame. To fix this I added 2mm of additional clearance, moving the sensor 2mm in the positive X direction. You might want to update the clearance in the Skynet or Marlin config if you want absolute accuracy, or you can edit the OpenSCAD so "Hole22OffsetX = Width - 20" to put it in the expected place (but watch your X axis for clearance).

description.text:
Deckel für Weizenbiergläser (in Bayern auch Weißbiergläser). Diese Deckel passen auf Gläser, die einen dicken Glasrand mit 80 mm Durchmesser haben. V1 hat kein Scharnier und wird einfach aufgeklippt. V2 hat ein Scharnier und kann zum trinken einfach hoch geklappt werden. Um einen größeren Öffnungswinkel zu erreichen, kann der Griff mit Hilfe eines Heißluftföns etwas nach oben gebogen werden.

Update 1:

V3 kann nun mit customizer mit eurem Namen versehen werden. Die Halteklammer ist jetzt länger und hält auch auf Gläsern ohne dicken Rand. Der Griff muss aber, wie abgebildet und oben erwähnt, um 45 Grad nach oben gebogen werden.

Update 2

V4 braucht nun nicht mehr gebogen zu werden. Der Text auf der Deckeloberseite wird nun vertieft auf dem Druckbett liegend gedruckt, dafür steht oben auf dem Deckel "Prosit!".
Da nur eine .scad-Datei vorhanden sein sollte, habe ich V3 mit der Endung .txt versehen.

Update 3

V4 funktioniert sehr gut, ist allerdings etwas problematisch zu drucken durch das hochstehende Scharnier. Außerdem kann das Scharnier bei geringer Layerhaftung bei der Montage brechen. Daher folgt nun V5:

  • Einfacher zu drucken
  • Scharnier unempfindlich gegenüber schlechter Layerhaftung
  • Name ist nun wieder auf der Oberseite des Deckels
  • Auch der Text an der Unterseite kann nun eingegeben werden

Bilder folgen beim nächsten Biergenuss.
